name: 2,4-dibromo-6-fluorophenol
Reason: Basic unit, benzene has a melting point of 5.5°C. Introducing a hydroxyl (OH) group increases polarity and the ability to form hydrogen bonds, suggesting an increase of approximately +80°C. Each bromine substituent, due to its large size and heavy mass, increases van der Waals forces, raising the melting point by approximately +20°C for each. Fluorine, being highly electronegative, increases the polarity further but to a lesser extent than OH, adding about +10°C to the melting point. Combining these effects, the additive influences of the substituents result in an overall increase in the melting point. However, one must also consider that dibromo substitution at ortho positions to each other might induce some steric hindrance, slightly lowering the melting point, estimated at about -5°C.
